answers.body_markdown:
There is no need for a new method for this. Simply in your `setPowerState()` method (which I would rename to `togglePowerState()` since this isn&#39;t a true &quot;setter&quot; method), add an if block at the end that prints your message if the power has been turned on:

```
// toggle power on/off  -- note method name has been changed
public static void togglePower() {
	powerOn = !powerOn;
	if (powerOn) {
		System.out.println(&quot;The power has been turned on&quot;);
	}
}
```

The advantage here is that the if block is called whenever the power state is toggled by this method. Note that this won&#39;t work if you can change your power state by other means, such as with a public field or a separate true &quot;setter&quot; method. If this is possible, then you will likely need to make powerState a &quot;bound property&quot; and use Java bean&#39;s PropertyChangeSupport along with a PropertyChangeListener, something which is probably over-kill for this assignment.

I would be remiss if I didn&#39;t mention the evils of over-use of static methods and fields, and while it may be a requirement of your project to use statics for this, in the long run, you likely wouldn&#39;t.

So, if this were my project, I&#39;d make powerOn a private *instance* field:

```
private boolean powerOn = false;

public boolean ispowerOn() {
    return powerOn;
}
```

and I&#39;d make it a &quot;bound property&quot; using the tools mentioned above:

```
// constant String to indicate which property we are listening to
public static final String POWER_ON = &quot;power on&quot;;

// prop change support: notifies listeners of changes in property
private PropertyChangeSupport support = new PropertyChangeSupport(this);

// our bound property
private boolean powerOn = false;

public boolean ispowerOn() {
    return powerOn;
}

// in the setter, notify any listeners by firing the support object
public void setpowerOn(boolean powerOn) {
    boolean oldValue = this.powerOn;
    boolean newValue = powerOn;
    this.powerOn = powerOn;
    support.firePropertyChange(POWER_ON, oldValue, newValue);
}

public void togglePower() {
    setpowerOn(!powerOn);  // this triggers the prop chng support
}
```

and we&#39;d have to allow outside classes the ability to add/remove property change listeners:

```
public void addPowerChangeListener(PropertyChangeListener pcListener) {
    support.addPropertyChangeListener(POWER_ON, pcListener);
}

public void removePowerChangeListener(PropertyChangeListener pcListener) {
    support.removePropertyChangeListener(pcListener);
}
```

The whole thing could look like:
```
public class Elevator {
    // constant String to indicate which property we are listening to
    public static final String POWER_ON = &quot;power on&quot;;

    // prop change support: notifies listeners of changes in property
    private PropertyChangeSupport support = new PropertyChangeSupport(this);

    // our bound property
    private boolean powerOn = false;

    public boolean ispowerOn() {
        return powerOn;
    }

    // in the setter, notify any listeners by firing the support object
    public void setpowerOn(boolean powerOn) {
        boolean oldValue = this.powerOn;
        boolean newValue = powerOn;
        this.powerOn = powerOn;
        support.firePropertyChange(POWER_ON, oldValue, newValue);
    }

    public void togglePower() {
        setpowerOn(!powerOn);  // this triggers the prop chng support
    }
    
    public void addPowerChangeListener(PropertyChangeListener pcListener) {
        support.addPropertyChangeListener(POWER_ON, pcListener);
    }
    
    public void removePowerChangeListener(PropertyChangeListener pcListener) {
        support.removePropertyChangeListener(pcListener);
    }
}
```

Then an outside class could easily add a property change listener, one that is notified whenever the powerOn property changes:

```
Elevator elevator = new Elevator();
elevator.addPowerChangeListener(pcEvent -&gt; {
    if (elevator.ispowerOn()) {
        // fired if the power is on
        System.out.println(&quot;The power is ON!&quot;);
    } else {
        // if you want output for when the power switches off
    }
});
```

A complete testing class could look like:

```
// imports
public class TestElevator {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Elevator elevator = new Elevator();
        elevator.addPowerChangeListener(pcEvent -&gt; {
            if (elevator.ispowerOn()) {
                // fired if the power is on
                System.out.println(&quot;The power is ON!&quot;);
            } else {
                // if you want output for when the power switches off
            }
        });
        
        @SuppressWarnings(&quot;resource&quot;)
        Scanner scan = new Scanner(System.in);
        
        boolean keepGoing = true;
        while (keepGoing) {
            System.out.print(&quot;Enter \&quot;on\&quot; to turn on power, \&quot;off\&quot; to turn it off, \&quot;toggle\&quot; to toggle it, and \&quot;quit\&quot; to quit: &quot;);
            String input = scan.nextLine();
            switch (input.toLowerCase()) {
            case &quot;on&quot;:
                elevator.setpowerOn(true);
                break;
            case &quot;off&quot;:
                elevator.setpowerOn(false);
                break;
            case &quot;toggle&quot;:
                elevator.togglePower();
                break;
            case &quot;quit&quot;:
                keepGoing = false;
                break;

            default:
                System.out.println(&quot;Invalid entry, try again&quot;);
                break;
            }
        }        
    }
    
}
```

First of all, a method called `setPowerState` suggests that you will set the power state to a value, so it should look like this:

```
    //power on/off
    public static void setPowerState(boolean po) {
        powerOn = po;
    }
```

You can also implement a toggler, but then you should name it `togglePowerState` and it should look like this:

```
    //power on/off
    public static void togglePowerState() {
        setPowerState(!getPowerState());
    }
```

But, in order to have that, we need to implement a proper getter, like this:

```
    public static boolean getPowerState() {
        return powerState;
    }
```

Notice that here we do not have a print, because you need to separate the logic from the UI/CLI, to save yourself from large headaches later. So, if you want to print the value, you can try it like this:

```
if (getPowerState()) {
    System.out.println(&quot;Power Reinstated&quot;);
}
```

Also, here we only had `static` methods, which are class-level. You may consider removing the `static` keyword, so they will be instance-level and that would allow your class to control the state of as many elevators as you want instead of a single one.

